\title{\freeeeg{}: Design and Roadmap for an\\
  Open-Hardware 128-Channel {EEG} Acquisition System\\
  \large Historical lineage, current-state audit, and alpha/beta plan}

\author[1]{Morgan Hough}
\affil[1]{NeuroTechX.\\
  \texttt{morgan.hough@gmail.com}}

\date{April 2026}

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\begin{document}
\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
\noindent
We present the design state, hardware audit, and alpha-to-beta development
roadmap of \freeeeg{}, an open-hardware 128-channel scalp
electroencephalography acquisition system evolving the NeuroIDSS
\freeeeg{}-alpha platform. The alpha board pairs an STMicroelectronics
STM32H743ZI Cortex-M7 microcontroller with sixteen Texas Instruments ADS131M08
24-bit delta-sigma ADCs distributed across six SPI buses, a timer/DMA cascade
providing sample-synchronous chip-select pulses, and a medical-grade digital-
and power-isolation barrier between subject and host. The accompanying cap
carries 130 dry Ag/AgCl passive electrodes on a 10/5 textile scaffold. We
situate the design in the lineage running from Nunez's biophysical framework
through Gevins' real-time cognitive-state engineering, Tucker's Geodesic
Sensor Net at Electrical Geodesics, Inc., and the active-electrode
breakthrough at BioSemi; and we identify Black et~al.\ 2017 (Open Ephys +
EEG) as the primary feature-for-feature comparison benchmark. We audit the
alpha board's peripheral inventory, flag the shortcomings of the stock
firmware, and present a phased firmware rewrite (packet-format freeze,
modular driver layer, first-class impedance mode, device-side timestamping,
watchdog and DFU support). We commit to a belt-pack wearable form factor
with a cap-mounted passive brain-box; reject the STM32MP2 upgrade path due
to battery-weight and EMI regressions; and plan an ESP32-S3 co-processor on
a beta revision for CircuitPython-compatible networking, LSL/WebSocket
delivery, and an Adafruit-ecosystem surface. Validation against the Black
et~al.\ eyes-closed alpha-vs-actiCHamp protocol is proposed as the beta
acceptance gate, with integrations targeted for Open Ephys GUI, MNE-CPP,
and BrainFlow on day one.
\end{abstract}

\tableofcontents
\vspace{1em}

% ===========================================================================
\section{Introduction}
% ===========================================================================

High-density electroencephalography was born from three simultaneous mid-1990s
breakthroughs: Paul Nunez's biophysical account of scalp potentials and the
corresponding Nyquist-style argument for densely sampling the
head~\citep{nunez1981electric,nunez1994laplacian}; Alan Gevins' real-time
cognitive-state engineering practice; and the first commercial 256-channel
EEG system, built at Neuroscan by Pflieger and Sands~\citep{pflieger1996256},
followed rapidly by the second 256-channel system at Electrical Geodesics,
Inc.~(EGI), which commercialized Tucker's Geodesic Sensor
Net~\citep{tucker1993geodesic}. Three decades later, academic and clinical
high-density EEG remains dominated by a handful of closed-ecosystem vendors
(BioSemi, Brain Products, ANT Neuro, Compumedics Neuroscan, g.tec,
NA300/GTEN, etc.), and the open-hardware movement has only recently
approached 100-channel counts.

The open-hardware track itself has matured quickly. OpenBCI~(2014) made
8-channel ADS1299 acquisition routinely accessible; Open Ephys (Siegle
et~al.\ 2017~\citep{siegle2017openephys}) generalized 512-channel
multichannel electrophysiology via a plugin GUI; Black et~al.\
2017~\citep{black2017openephyseeg} adapted that platform to 128-channel
human EEG and validated it side-by-side against a BrainVision actiCHamp
clinical amplifier. Cardona-\'{A}lvarez et~al.\
2023~\citep{cardona2023openbci} published the most detailed production
framework for an open-hardware BCI to date, built on OpenBCI Cyton with
a Raspberry Pi acquisition server, distributed Kafka-based message
fan-out, and a custom three-layer driver stack; their work documents
the OpenBCI Cyton+Daisy 8$\to$16 channel interleaving artifact that
FreeEEG128's synchronized 16$\times$ADS131M08 architecture eliminates.
More recent entries --- PiEEG, IronBCI, HackEEG, BIOADC,
Neurogate~OctaFlow --- cover an expanding range of channel counts, packaging,
and wireless protocols, but none have delivered 128-channel density with
full medical-grade isolation, free licensing of both firmware and hardware,
and first-class support for the full open real-time stack (Open Ephys GUI +
MNE-CPP + BrainFlow + LSL + BIDS-EEG).

\freeeeg{} aims at that gap. The alpha revision (NeuroIDSS, Vivancos 2023
\citep{vivancos2023mindbigdata}) exists as fewer than five physical units
worldwide. One is on the author's bench; the present paper describes the
design audit, the firmware-rewrite roadmap, and the planned beta revision.

% ===========================================================================
\section{Historical lineage}
% ===========================================================================

\subsection{Theoretical foundations --- Nunez}

Nunez's book \textit{Electric Fields of the Brain}~\citep{nunez1981electric}
(second edition with Srinivasan~\citep{nunez2006electric}) remains the
canonical biophysical reference. Three arguments continue to shape hardware
design: (i)~scalp potential is spatially low-pass-filtered relative to
cortical sources, with the skull acting as a \SIrange{2}{3}{\centi\metre}
smoothing kernel; (ii)~reference electrode choice is not neutral, and
software-defined referencing (surface Laplacian, average reference) is
required for source-localization work~\citep{nunez1994laplacian}; and
(iii)~volume conduction ensures that no scalp sensor sees a single
source. Each of these motivates the channel-count race of the 1990s: below
roughly 64 electrodes the surface-Laplacian math does not pay off.

\subsection{Engineering pioneer --- Gevins}

Alan Gevins founded EEG Systems Laboratory~(1980) and SAM Technology~(1986),
and by the early 1990s had pushed EEG hardware practice toward 64 and 128
channels with sustained real-time cognitive-state analysis. His
``deblurring'' methods, combining MRI-derived geometry with scalp EEG to
estimate cortical-surface potential~\citep{gevins1997working}, predate
modern source localization and established the protocol templates for
sustained-attention and mental-workload studies that the field still uses.

\subsection{Engineering breakthrough --- Tucker and EGI}

Don Tucker's Geodesic Sensor Net~\citep{tucker1993geodesic}, commercialized
as Electrical Geodesics, Inc., is the direct ancestor of the \freeeeg{}
form factor. The saline-sponge electrode array on a tension-distributed
elastic polymer scaffold solved the practical application-workflow problem
that had made high-density EEG impractical outside specialist labs:
application time dropped from \mbox{60+ minutes} (paste-based) to
approximately five minutes. EGI built the \emph{second} 256-channel EEG
system in the world; the present author served as its first software
engineering manager during the mid-1990s. Ramesh Srinivasan, Nunez's
co-author on the second edition of \textit{Electric Fields of the
Brain}~\citep{nunez2006electric} and now Professor of Cognitive Sciences
and Biomedical Engineering at UC~Irvine, was an early member of EGI, which
is why EGI's product line shipped with surface-Laplacian and average-
reference montaging as first-class software features from the start.

\subsection{The commercial high-density era}

Table~\ref{tab:commercial} summarizes the commercial high-density
landscape. Common themes that \freeeeg{} inherits, or explicitly moves
past, include a pervasive reliance on proprietary caps, connectors, amps,
and software; the emergence of belt-pack amps (ANT, BrainProducts LiveAmp)
after a decade of desk-tethered designs; the \emph{first} high-density
active-electrode system at BioSemi in the late 1990s, which remains the
standard against which movement-tolerant recording is measured; and the
eventual standardization of per-channel impedance-check and reference-
flexibility as table-stakes features.

