\subsection{The very-high-density frontier --- g.Pangolin and 1024-channel EEG}
\label{sec:vhd}

A second revolution has been quietly underway since roughly 2020: the
move from ``HD-EEG'' (64--128 channels) to \emph{ultra- or very-high-
density EEG} (VHD-EEG / uHD-EEG, 256--1024$+$ channels). The theoretical
driver is a refinement of Nunez's spatial-Nyquist argument ---
Grover and Venkatesh (cited in Schreiner et~al.\ 2024) propose, on
information-theoretic grounds, that the scalp's spatial bandwidth
demands not hundreds but \emph{thousands} of electrode positions to
capture all of the information it carries.

The state-of-the-art commercial VHD system is \textbf{g.tec's
g.Pangolin}~\citep{schreiner2024pangolin}, a 1024-channel-capable
uHD-EEG platform operating at a 256-channel density in the published
demonstration. Key specifications:

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
\item Up to \textbf{1024 channels} via four g.HIamp 256-channel amplifiers.
\item Flexible printed-circuit electrode grids of 16 channels each, with
gold-plated electrode points arranged at \textbf{8.6 mm inter-electrode
distance} and \textbf{5.9 mm electrode diameter}.
\item An \textbf{active pre-amplifier per grid} (fixed gain 10) before
the back-end g.HIamp.
\item Wet electrodes with conductive paste (Elefix) under an adhesive
layer designed to prevent bridging and crosstalk.
\item 24-bit ADC resolution, up to 38.4 kHz sample rate per channel.
\item Authors of Schreiner et~al.\ (2024) include Christoph Guger
(founder of g.tec) among g.tec-affiliated researchers.
\end{itemize}

Schreiner et~al.\ use this system at 256-channel density to demonstrate
\textbf{95.2\% classification accuracy} of channels as anterior or
posterior to the central sulcus via somatosensory-evoked-potential
phase-reversal analysis --- a level of functional precision previously
only achievable with surgically implanted ECoG.

Closely related theoretical and methodological work includes Shirazi,
Onton \& Makeig (2025)~\citep{shirazi2025scalp}, who simulate scalp EEG
from ultra-high-density ECoG to quantify cortex-to-scalp projection
patterns; Liu et~al.\ (2018)~\citep{liu2018density}, who establish the
systematic benefits of density, head modeling, and source localization
for reconstructing large-scale brain networks; and Fiedler
et~al.\ (2022)~\citep{fiedler2022256dry}, whose 256-channel dry cap
covers the dry-electrode side of the VHD spectrum.

\paragraph{Where \freeeeg{} sits in this landscape.} We are deliberately
\emph{not} claiming VHD-EEG status. The open-hardware frontier at 256$+$
channels remains commercial-only as of April 2026. \freeeeg{} occupies
the ``affordable mid-density open-hardware'' niche: higher channel count
than OpenBCI (8--16) and Open Ephys~+~EEG / Black 2017 (64--128), lower
than g.Pangolin (1024), at roughly one to two orders of magnitude lower
cost than the commercial systems at comparable channel counts. A natural
upgrade path (``FreeEEG256'') on the same STM32H743 + ADS131M08 chassis
is plausible --- thirty-two ADCs across six SPI buses plus a second-
stage cable design --- and would put open hardware meaningfully closer
to the VHD threshold, but that is explicitly not within the present
roadmap.

\subsection{The open-hardware generation}

\freeeeg{} sits at the current frontier of open-hardware EEG.
Section~\ref{sec:related} presents the feature-level comparison in detail.

% ===========================================================================
\section{Related open-hardware work}
\label{sec:related}
% ===========================================================================

Table~\ref{tab:landscape} enumerates the open-hardware EEG projects relevant
to \freeeeg{}. Two observations matter for design decisions. First, no
existing open-hardware project reaches 128 channels without compromising
on either licensing (Black et~al.\ 2017 is CC-BY-NC-SA 3.0 IGO, restricting
commercial use) or form factor (every 128+~ch system is desk-tethered
rather than wearable). Second, the industry-default single-chip ADC for
these projects is the Texas Instruments ADS1299 (eight channels, 24~bit);
\freeeeg{}-alpha instead uses sixteen ADS131M08s, inheriting the
FreeEEG32-beta demonstration that this chip family achieves research-grade
noise performance at lower cost.

