\subsection{Microcontroller and clocking}

The STM32H743ZI~\citep{st_stm32h743} (Cortex-M7 at 480~MHz, 2~MB flash,
1~MB SRAM, double-precision FPU) is the correct choice for this system and
is retained across the alpha$\to$beta transition (Section~\ref{sec:mcu}).
Three capabilities explain why no other microcontroller in the
Adafruit-supported ESP32 lineage or the Cortex-M4 cost-down tiers would
work: (i)~six independent SPI peripherals, required to read sixteen
ADS131M08s without daisy-chain penalties; (ii)~a TIM1/TIM8 cascade routed
through DMA in circular mode onto a GPIO port, generating
sample-synchronous chip-select pulses across all sixteen chips with zero
CPU involvement; and (iii)~a radio-quiet substrate and low-jitter clock
tree adjacent to a 24-bit $\Delta\Sigma$ analog front-end.

An external FXO-SM7 oscillator drives the ADC master clock. The STM32's
HSE is a 16~MHz crystal and an LSE 32.768~kHz crystal is populated for
RTC use (currently unused by the stock firmware).

\subsection{Isolation and power}

The board implements a textbook medical-isolation topology. On the digital
side, an Analog Devices ADuM3160 full-speed USB isolator gates the host
link; an ADuM1402BRWZ quad digital isolator handles the SPI/UART path to
the programming headers; and two ISO7341C 3-channel isolators sit on the
SPI fabric that reaches the ADC bank. On the power side, a Texas
Instruments SN6505B push-pull transformer driver feeds a W\"urth
750315371 transformer, producing the isolated 5~V analog island; this
is then regulated by three Texas Instruments LP5907 ultra-low-noise LDOs
(6.5~\textmu V~RMS, $\sim$82~dB PSRR at 1~kHz) generating AVDD, VDD,
and IOVDD, with an Analog Devices ADP7118 serving as an alternate
high-PSRR LDO. Voltage references are supplied by a REF2025 (ADC Vref)
and an ADR4525 (precision reference). The upstream USB rail is
deliberately a \emph{non-critical} rail, which is why the stock
firmware can operate adequately from a consumer USB power bank.

\subsection{Peripheral-by-peripheral audit}

Table~\ref{tab:peripherals} summarizes the STM32 peripherals presently
configured in the stock firmware's \texttt{.ioc} file, cross-referenced
against \texttt{Src/main.c:2237--2255}. Notable findings for the
firmware rewrite include: (i) the D-Cache is disabled, a workaround for
cached DMA-buffer staleness which we will replace with an MPU-backed
non-cacheable region; (ii) the \texttt{.ioc} simultaneously configures
\texttt{USB\_DEVICE} and \texttt{USB\_OTG\_HS}, with the virtual-pin
assignment labeling the device \texttt{VS\_USB\_DEVICE\_CDC\_HS}, but
PB14/PB15 are set to \texttt{Device\_Only\_FS}\,---\,an HS-versus-FS
conflict that will be resolved by locking to FS because the ADuM3160
isolator is full-speed only; (iii) legacy \texttt{ad7779.c/h} files from
the FreeEEG32 predecessor remain in the tree, and commented-out W5500
(WIZnet SPI-to-Ethernet) bring-up code from FreeSmartEEG is present but
unused; and (iv) neither the IWDG watchdog nor the RTC is initialized,
despite the LSE crystal being populated.

