USART1  & Isolated UART (ADuM1402) --- debug \texttt{printf} & -- \\
TIM1    & Sample-sync CS pulse generator (TRGO $\to$ DMA) & DMA1 Stream~7, Circular \\
TIM8    & Clock source for TIM1 cascade (TRGO) & DMA1 Stream~4, Circular \\
USB (FS) CDC & Host data link via ADuM3160 & -- \\
DMA1 + DMA2 + MDMA & SPI traffic + TIM cascades & enabled \\
IWDG / WWDG & \textbf{not configured} & -- \\
RTC (LSE 32.768\,kHz) & \textbf{not used} & -- \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

% ===========================================================================
\section{Enclosure, form factor, and cabling}
\label{sec:enclosure}
% ===========================================================================

At 128~channels the device cannot reasonably be head-worn. The 130-lead
harness, plus the 1.5~mm DIN connector field, plus a battery and amp PCB
exceeds a wearable head-mount mass and volume budget by an order of
magnitude; every commercial high-density system at 128~channels or above
solves this the same way (belt-pack or shoulder-pack amp, bundled
shielded cable to a cap-mounted passive fan-out). The \freeeeg{}-beta
form factor accepts this:

\begin{center}
\small
\begin{tabular}{c}
Cap (head-worn): 130 dry electrodes $\to$ 130$\times$ 1.5\,mm DIN \\
$\downarrow$ \\
Brain-box (cap-mounted, passive fan-out) \\
$\downarrow$ \\
1--2 multipole quick-disconnect (HD D-sub HD78 or LEMO EGG.4B) \\
$\downarrow$ 30--60\,cm shielded bundle \\
Amp box (belt-pack): \freeeeg{} PCB + battery \\
$\downarrow$ USB-CDC (or Wi-Fi on beta) \\
Host PC
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

Battery chemistry is flexible because the ADuM3160 + SN6505B + LP5907
chain already rejects upstream ripple at audio frequencies. The alpha
stays with a consumer USB power bank; the beta plans a 2S~18650 Li-ion
pack with an ideal-diode OR between USB-C input and pack, and an LT3045
class ultra-low-noise LDO for the input rail. A Samsung PRO~Endurance
microSDXC is recommended for sustained write loads; the stock firmware's
FatFS is configured for FAT32, so SDXC cards must be reformatted before
first mount.

The beta-rev connector strategy is \emph{HD D-Sub HD78} at the
brain-box$\leftrightarrow$amp break, retaining the 1.5~mm DIN at the
electrode end for subject-contact safety. Two HD78 shells cover 130
leads; the metal shell provides a known-good shield reference and
cleanability, and any clinical technician can mate them. An upgrade path
to LEMO EGG.4B multipole connectors is open for a clinical-grade variant.

% ===========================================================================
\section{MCU and companion-processor choice}
\label{sec:mcu}
% ===========================================================================

We evaluated upgrade paths from the current STM32H743ZI.
Table~\ref{tab:mcu-options} summarizes. The verdict: retain H743 as the
acquisition engine; treat STM32N6 as the only interesting STM32 upgrade
(for on-device ML via the Neural-ART NPU); reject STM32MP2 as wrong-tool-
for-task; and add an ESP32-S3 co-processor on the beta board to deliver
Wi-Fi/BLE, CircuitPython compatibility, STEMMA QT / Adafruit sensor
ecosystem access, and native LSL/WebSocket publishing.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering\small
\caption{STM32 upgrade evaluation. Pricing and SKU availability should
be re-verified with current distributor data.}
\label{tab:mcu-options}
\begin{tabular}{llp{4cm}l}
\toprule
Option & Clock & Key delta vs H743 & Verdict \\
\midrule
STM32H753ZI      & 480\,MHz & + crypto accelerator & No; crypto on ESP32-S3 \\
STM32H723/H725ZG & 550\,MHz & +15\%, less RAM & No; RAM regression \\
STM32H7A3/B3ZI   & 280\,MHz & 2\,MB flash + 1.4\,MB RAM, USB-HS PHY & Marginal \\
STM32H755/H757ZI & 480+240\,MHz & M7 + M4 dual-core & No; doesn't give Adafruit alignment \\
STM32H7R / H7S   & 600\,MHz & XiP-flash architecture & No \\
\textbf{STM32N6} & 800\,MHz & \textbf{Cortex-M55 + Helium + on-die NPU} & \textbf{Consider} if on-device ML wanted \\
STM32MP2         & A35 Linux + M33 & Runs Linux on-chip & \textbf{No}; 10$\times$ battery-weight regression, HDI PCB required, EMI concerns \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\paragraph{Why ESP32 cannot replace the STM32.}
A full swap to an ESP32-S3 or ESP32-P4 fails on three technical axes: SPI
bus count (S3 has 2 usable vs our requirement of 6; P4 has 3); absence of
the TIM-cascade-to-DMA-to-GPIO sample-sync primitive; and WiFi radio
emissions coupling into a 24-bit $\Delta\Sigma$ analog front-end. These
objections do not apply to an 8-channel teaching board such as Neurogate
OctaFlow, which is why ESP32-C3 is correct there. For 128-channel medical-
grade acquisition the STM32 is the right silicon.

\subsection{Companion processor for the beta revision --- Raspberry Pi Zero 2W}
\label{sec:pi}

The alpha board communicates with a host computer via USB-CDC. The beta
revision needs to add wireless host connectivity, on-device scripting,
LSL / BrainFlow / MNE-Python availability, and an operator-facing web
UI, so that the whole system can be carried in a shoulder-strap pack and
used without a tethered laptop. We considered two architectures for this
companion:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*]
\item An on-PCB \textbf{ESP32-S3} co-processor connected to the STM32H743
over isolated SPI, running ESP-IDF or CircuitPython, re-emitting the
framed EEG stream over Wi-Fi/BLE/WebSocket/LSL.
\item A \textbf{Raspberry Pi Zero 2W} (quad-core Cortex-A53, 512~MB RAM,
dual-band Wi-Fi, BLE~5) sharing the enclosure with the FreeEEG128 PCB,
connecting over plain USB-CDC, running Raspberry Pi OS~64-bit~Lite with
the full Python stack pre-installed.
\end{enumerate}

Table~\ref{tab:companion} compares the two paths. We adopt \textbf{option~2}.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering\small
\caption{Companion-processor trade study.}
\label{tab:companion}
\begin{tabular}{p{0.3\textwidth}p{0.3\textwidth}p{0.3\textwidth}}
\toprule
\textbf{Factor} & \textbf{ESP32-S3 on-PCB} & \textbf{Raspberry Pi Zero 2W} \\
\midrule
Additional firmware project & ESP-IDF or CircuitPython, $\sim$2--4 weeks & \textbf{None} — stock Raspberry Pi OS \\
Native Python / pylsl / BrainFlow / MNE-Python & Requires porting or staged progression & \textbf{Day one} via \texttt{pip install} \\
Algorithm iteration on-device & No (recompile + flash) & \textbf{Yes} (SSH + Python REPL) \\
Operator web UI & Would need to write & \textbf{FastAPI + browser in a day} \\
STM32 $\leftrightarrow$ host link & New isolated SPI bridge + isolator design & \textbf{USB-CDC on existing ADuM3160} \\
MNE-CPP integration & Requires Stage~2 native plugin & Stage~1 LSL loopback suffices \\
Average power & $\sim$0.75\,W & $\sim$1.25\,W \\
Boot time & Instant & 15--30\,s (mitigated by auto-start) \\
PCB footprint & 25$\times$18\,mm module & 65$\times$30\,mm SBC \\
Storage & On-chip flash & microSD + optional USB drive \\
Adafruit-ecosystem pedagogy & CircuitPython native & Via Blinka shim on Linux \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The decisive points are the elimination of the second firmware project
(deleting two to four weeks of work from the beta critical path) and the
removal of the staged MNE-CPP integration complexity. The 50\% power-draw
increase is tolerable --- a 2S 18650 pack (25~Wh) still gives 6--8~h of
session at total system draw $\sim$3--4~W, which is more than enough for
typical research paradigms. The boot-time concern is mitigated by
configuring systemd to auto-start the capture and LSL services on boot,
and by adding a small e-ink status strip to the enclosure so the operator
sees when the device is ready.

\subsection{Pre-validation with synthetic data on the Pi Zero 2W}
\label{sec:prevalidate}

A significant advantage of the SBC architecture is that the entire host
stack can be validated with simulated EEG data before the FreeEEG128
firmware rewrite completes. We plan the following benchmark suite to
run on the Pi Zero 2W in advance of alpha bring-up:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*]
\item \textbf{Base Python speed}: NumPy FFT on a 128$\times$25\,000
complex array; target under 50\,ms.
\item \textbf{LSL local loopback}: an outlet and inlet pair in the same
process pushing 128-channel float32 samples at 250\,Hz; measure pull
latency and sustained throughput for 60\,s.
\item \textbf{BrainFlow \texttt{SYNTHETIC\_BOARD}}: stream synthetic EEG
for 5\,min via BrainFlow; confirm zero sample drops.
\item \textbf{EEG-ExPy packaged experiments}: run NeuroTechX EEG-ExPy's
Visual~P300, SSVEP, and N170 paradigms with the synthetic backend;
confirm experimental loop completes without dropped frames.
\item \textbf{MNE-Python online preprocessing}: filter and ICA on a
5-minute synthetic epoch; time and memory profile.
\item \textbf{BIDS-EEG writer}: write a synthetic dataset out to BIDS
and verify with the BIDS validator.
\item \textbf{Wall-power draw}: 10-minute LSL loopback measured at a
USB power meter; confirms the battery-life budget above.
\end{enumerate}

When the FreeEEG128 firmware is ready, the only change to the host stack
is swapping the BrainFlow synthetic-board backend for the real-device
backend. Everything downstream (LSL outlet, MNE processing, EEG-ExPy
paradigm hooks, BIDS writer, web UI) is validated and stable.

\subsection{Optional: OpenWrt router as a recording appliance}
\label{sec:openwrt}

For portable-lab deployments and multi-client recording scenarios, an
OpenWrt-based Wi-Fi router (e.g., GL.iNet GL-MT3000 ``Beryl AX'',
$\sim$USD~80, pocketable, USB~3 port, Wi-Fi~6) can be added as a
dedicated network appliance between the Pi-borne FreeEEG128 and one or
more recording / analysis laptops. OpenWrt provides:

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
\item A dedicated SSID (``EEG-NET'') with zero extraneous traffic,
eliminating LSL~UDP packet loss under lab network contention.
\item Router-enforced QoS prioritizing LSL traffic.
\item A system-wide NTP (or, with compatible hardware, PTP) authority,
providing a common time base across all clients with faster convergence
than pure LSL time correction.
\item Packet-level recording redundancy: a lightweight sniffer service
on the router can dump LSL traffic to a USB stick, so the stream is
preserved even if a recording laptop crashes.
\item WireGuard / OpenVPN ingress for remote monitoring, keeping the
subject's recording network off the venue infrastructure.
\end{itemize}

For single-subject bench recordings with one laptop, the router adds
complexity with little benefit and can be skipped (the Pi can run as a
Wi-Fi access point directly). The architecture earns its keep in field
deployments, hyperscanning paradigms, and any recording session that
must be independent of venue Wi-Fi. OpenWrt is deliberately
\emph{optional} in the roadmap; the Pi-and-laptop baseline is the
default.

% ===========================================================================
\section{Firmware rewrite}
% ===========================================================================

The stock alpha firmware was written against STM32CubeMX 1.5.1 in approximately
2021--2022. It demonstrates working communication with all sixteen ADS131M08
chips at 250~Hz and emits raw 24-bit samples over USB-CDC to a host. It is,
however, fundamentally research-prototype quality. Table~\ref{tab:fw-plan}
summarizes the planned rewrite.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering\small
\caption{Firmware rewrite plan. Phase ordering assumes a baseline capture
from the stock firmware precedes any code change.}
\label{tab:fw-plan}
\begin{tabular}{llp{7cm}}
\toprule
Phase & Id & Scope \\
\midrule
Baseline & P0.1 & Power-on + CDC enumeration \\
         & P0.2 & 60\,s shorted-input noise floor + 5\,min eyes-closed baseline \\
         & P0.3 & STM32 pin audit $\to$ \texttt{docs/alpha-pinmap.md} \\
Protocol & P1.0 & Wire-packet format: magic, length, seq, device \textmu s timestamp, ADC status, 128$\times$int24, IMU, CRC32 \\
         & P1.1 & Host command protocol: \texttt{START}, \texttt{STOP}, \texttt{SET\_RATE}, \texttt{SET\_GAIN}, \texttt{LEAD\_OFF\_START}, \texttt{LEAD\_OFF\_STOP}, \texttt{GET\_CAPS}, \texttt{REBOOT\_DFU} \\
Rewrite  & P1.2 & Regenerate \texttt{.ioc} on current CubeMX; lock USB to FS \\
         & P1.3 & Firmware scaffold: \texttt{hal/}, \texttt{drivers/}, \texttt{transport/}, \texttt{services/} \\
         & P1.4 & ADS131M08 driver --- per-sample CRC forwarding, drop counter, TIM/DMA CS cascade (highest risk) \\
         & P1.5 & LSM6DS3 IMU driver + interleaved IMU packets \\
         & P1.6 & USB-CDC framed transport, MPU non-cacheable DMA region, re-enabled D-Cache \\
         & P1.7 & Acquisition service, IWDG, RTC timestamping, boot banner, dead-code purge \\
         & P1.8 & \textbf{Impedance mode as first-class feature} --- ADS131M08 lead-off current injection + per-channel magnitude/phase \\
         & P1.9 & SD logging service + DFU-jump command \\
Host     & P2   & Python pyserial capture $\to$ LSL outlet + BIDS-EEG writer + FIFF writer + quality dashboard \\
         & P2b  & BrainFlow board definition (upstream) \\
         & P2c  & MNE-CPP native acquisition plugin (upstream PR to \texttt{mne-tools/mne-cpp}) \\
Validation & P3 & Eyes-closed 8--14\,Hz alpha replication of Black et~al.\ 2017 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

% ===========================================================================
\section{Host and application support}
\label{sec:apps}
% ===========================================================================

We target the full open real-time EEG stack on day one of the beta release:

Host-side software runs on the beta's Pi Zero 2W companion
(Section~\ref{sec:pi}), with Raspberry Pi OS~64-bit~Lite as the base
operating system.

\begin{description}[leftmargin=*]
\item[Lab Streaming Layer (LSL).] Python host publishes an LSL outlet
per device; Labstreamer TTL markers ingest as a second LSL stream.
\item[BrainFlow.] We write and upstream a \texttt{Board} definition,
which pulls in MNE-LSL, LabRecorder, Timeflux, NeuroPype, and OpenViBE
for free.
\item[Open Ephys GUI.] An acquisition plugin, modeled on the Rhythm
Node, ingests \freeeeg{} frames into the Open Ephys GUI plugin
architecture.
\item[MNE-CPP / MNE Scan.] Three-stage integration. Stage 1 is free via
LSL loopback through MNE Scan's existing LSL adapter. Stage 2 is a
native \texttt{freeeeg128adapter} plugin modeled on
\texttt{applications/mne\_scan/plugins/lsladapter/} and upstreamed via
PR. Stage 3 adds FIFF writing in the Python host so that MNE-Python
users read captures via \texttt{mne.io.read\_raw\_fif()} with no
translation layer.
\item[BIDS-EEG.] Python host writes BIDS-compliant datasets with event
markers and per-channel impedance metadata.
\item[EEG-ExPy.] NeuroTechX's EEG-ExPy paradigm library
(\href{https://neurotechx.github.io/eeg-expy/}{neurotechx.github.io/eeg-expy})
provides packaged implementations of Visual~P300, SSVEP, N170, and
auditory-oddball experiments. These are used for the pre-validation
benchmarks in Section~\ref{sec:prevalidate} and remain available as
ready-to-run paradigms for users of the finished device.
\item[Operator web UI.] A FastAPI application on the Pi serves a
browser-based session control and quality-monitoring dashboard, so that
the subject's device needs no tethered laptop during a recording
session.
\end{description}

\subsection{Comparison-plot}

Figure~\ref{fig:landscape} places \freeeeg{} against the open-hardware
landscape on the channel-count versus BOM-cost plane.

<<landscape-plot, fig=TRUE, echo=FALSE, results=hide, height=3.5, width=6>>=
boards <- data.frame(
  name = c("OpenBCI\nCyton","OpenBCI\nGanglion","HackEEG",
           "PiEEG-16","IronBCI","Neurogate\nOctaFlow",
           "BIOADC","FreeEEG32\nbeta","Open Ephys\n+ EEG",
           "FreeEEG128\n(this work)","g.Pangolin\n(VHD SOTA)"),
  channels = c(8, 4, 32, 16, 8, 8, 32, 32, 128, 128, 1024),
  price    = c(1000, 500, 450, 600, 300, 200, 400, 500, 3000, 900, 100000),
  res      = c(24, 24, 24, 24, 24, 24, 24, 24, 16, 24, 24),
  pch      = c(1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 2, 19, 17)
)
op <- par(mar=c(4.2, 4.2, 0.5, 0.5), cex=0.85)
plot(boards$price, boards$channels,
     log="xy",
     xlab="Estimated BOM / retail cost (USD, log scale)",
     ylab="Channel count (log scale)",
     pch=boards$pch, cex=1.6,
     xlim=c(150, 200000), ylim=c(3, 2000))
text(boards$price, boards$channels, labels=boards$name, pos=4, offset=0.6, cex=0.7)
abline(h=128, lty=3, col="gray50")
abline(h=256, lty=3, col="gray70")
legend("bottomleft",
       legend=c("Other open HW","Open Ephys + EEG (Black 2017)","FreeEEG128","g.Pangolin VHD SOTA"),
       pch=c(1, 2, 19, 17), bty="n", cex=0.8)
par(op)
@

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.95\textwidth]{paper-landscape-plot}
\caption{Open-hardware EEG landscape on the channel-count vs.\ cost plane,
with g.Pangolin~\citep{schreiner2024pangolin} added as the commercial
VHD-EEG state-of-the-art reference point.
\freeeeg{} and Open Ephys~+~EEG (Black et~al.\ 2017) are the
only 128-channel open entries; \freeeeg{} achieves this at approximately
one-third the cost of Open Ephys~+~EEG and with 24-bit ADC resolution
versus the Intan RHD family's 16-bit. g.Pangolin demonstrates the
VHD-EEG frontier at roughly $10^2$--$10^3$ times the cost.}
\label{fig:landscape}
\end{figure}

% ===========================================================================
\section{Validation plan}
\label{sec:validation}
% ===========================================================================

The acceptance gate for calling anything ``beta'' is a direct replication
of Black et~al.~\citep{black2017openephyseeg}: eyes-closed 8--14~Hz alpha
power and SNR, side-by-side against a BrainVision actiCHamp (or another
clinical-grade reference amplifier). The same subject, the same room, the
same electrode montage where possible. We report per-channel average
power and broadband SNR matching the Black paradigm, plus the drop-counter
and impedance metadata that the firmware rewrite delivers. Raw data and
analysis notebooks are published under \texttt{docs/validation/} at the
same moment the beta schematic is released.

Secondary validation targets, sequenced after the acceptance gate:
an auditory-oddball P300 latency confirmed within 20~ms against a
Labstreamer photodiode/TTL ground truth; a steady-state visual evoked
potential (SSVEP) spectrum at 6, 7.5, 10, and 15~Hz; and a resting-state
connectivity replication against one of the large publicly available
datasets.

% ===========================================================================
\section{Open questions and next steps}
% ===========================================================================

Open items that require decisions during Phase~B0 of the beta rev:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*]
\item Black's \textit{Brain Topography} DOI for Tucker 1993 --- currently
cited from Tucker's 1993 \textit{Electroencephalography and Clinical
Neurophysiology} paper; check whether there is a better primary for the
Geodesic Sensor Net.
\item Whether to enable the Neural-ART NPU via STM32N6 on the beta, or
keep STM32H743 and plan on-device ML only as a software add-on.
\item Whether the \freeeeg{} hardware license moves from the upstream
NeuroIDSS AGPL-3.0 to CERN-OHL-S-v2 (strongly recommended; AGPL is a
software license and is legally murky on hardware).
\item Connector choice for the brain-box$\leftrightarrow$amp link:
HD D-Sub HD78 (budget path) or LEMO EGG.4B (clinical-grade path).
\item Whether to reproduce Black et~al.'s commercial-cap adapter chain
as a sister \freeeeg{}-amp-only product for users with existing EasyCap
hardware.
\item Whether to ship a reference OpenWrt configuration
(Section~\ref{sec:openwrt}) for portable-lab deployments, or leave that
to users.
\end{enumerate}

Immediate next steps (this week): power-on and enumeration check of the
alpha unit in hand; baseline noise-floor and eyes-closed alpha capture
with the stock firmware; STM32 pin audit to freeze the pinout before any
firmware changes; lock the wire-packet and command-protocol specs as the
alpha$\to$beta carry-over artifacts.

